 &lt;p&gt;ç¬¬ä¸€æ¬¡ç”¨è‹±æ–‡å†™å‘¨è®°ï¼Œç”šä¸ºä¸é€‚åº”ã€‚&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;The study this week is mainly divided into the following aspects:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
&lt;li&gt;I submitted the survey on the security strength of classic and post-quantum public key cryptography. Luping Wang then gave some comments and suggestions for improvement on the survey notes. Firstly, the research content of classic cryptographic schemes is not yet sufficient. In the next stage, I will look for more classic cryptographic schemes, including but not limited to the classic schemes on the NIST standard. I will also add some other classic schemes to the post-quantum cryptography section. Secondly, I still need to add some more content, such as commercial application cryptographic schemes, including scheme parameters or standards currently used by domestic and international government departments and large enterprises. After the final exam, I will organize the notes into the form of the first draft of the paper. Since the final exam is coming, I will focus more on reviewing my professional courses. Before the Spring Festival, I will finish the draft.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;In this week, I wrote two course reports about my gains and thoughts. When I reread Cryptanalysis of Full LowMC and LowMC-M with Algebraic Techniques, I find I understand it more deeply and solved some problems left. As for the Network Security Protocols, I combined the experience of my Graduation Project and the reading of the paper Koinonia: Verifiable E-Voting with Long-term Privacy, and wrote a detailed report. Summarizing what I have learned regularly can help me gain a deeper understanding. I also plan to post the course reports, notes and weekly reports written this semester to my personal blog for archives. Next week, I will take 2 course exams, so I spent some time reviewing these 2 courses as well.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

